I’d say AI is wrong. So let’s say you solve a certain day most commonly in a 10 minute span (of course some are outside that, but we are ballparking it). Let’s assume it’s random in that span—which it isn’t. Then pick one of your times there. Your chance of getting that identical time the next time would be 1/600 (10 x 60 seconds).  Your chance of getting it the second time would be 1/360,000–not high but already less than what the AI said. Now getting three in a 110 puzzle span would be much lower than that. Then consider that they aren’t randomly spread out during that time, but are bunched up near your average, so getting three at a time near your average would be even less than that. Then consider that you are not looking to repeat that specific time—just any one of those times repeated three times, that’s MUCH lower. Then consider that you are just one person, if you had a thousand people then likely one of those people would have that outcome and might post it of they noticed and paid attention—and we are talking about many more people than that. So, not totally surprising.
So for example it only takes 23 people in a room to have a 50 percent likelihood of two having the same birthday, and 88 for three birthdays. Same idea.

@AG
Ok to add on to my comment above. I asked AI, for a bell curve with an average of 30 minutes and a standard deviation of 10 minutes (which is extremely generous, I think your actual distribution is probably tighter than that) what the probability of getting three outcomes of the same number of seconds in 110 tries; and the answer is 24%. Not very surprising at all. 
So now you know—half the battle with using AI is asking the right question.

